I get his point, to each their own, live and let live - except that killing sentient animals for sustenance is not necessary anymore as it once was. we grow enough food to feed billions of animals just to slaughter them, and still we have hungry children all over. i.e. it's a distribution problem, not a production problem. i think it's revolutionary to stand up for the little guy and strive to end animal exploitation. like Che says, "the true revolutionary is guided by a great feeling of love. It is impossible to think of a genuine revolutionary lacking this quality." Once we see that adequate nutrition can be obtained without slaughtering animals, and get profit out of food industry, i think we can socially evolve as a species. imo if we can end murder of animals we get closer to ending murder of humans too, and i think it's revolutionary to fight for that future. 

Rosa also said "the most revolutionary thing one can do is to proclaim loudly what is happening". If we give the same love of dogs/cats to other animals, vegans won't have to remind you of the animal genocide happening under our noses. maybe immortal technique just needs to challenge his convictions a little more on the subject (e.g. omnivores die each day of preventable chronic disease - vegans are not all skinny or malnourished, etc). the way he challenged mine with his music.

